definition.value: A cellobiose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid that is acetylpyruvic acid in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group is replaced by a hydroxy group.

A pyrimidine nucleoside in which cytosine is attached to D-arabinofuranose via a beta-N(1)-glycosidic bond. Used mainly in the treatment of leukaemia, especially acute non-lymphoblastic leukaemia, cytarabine is an antimetabolite antineoplastic agent that inhibits the synthesis of DNA. It also has antiviral and immunosuppressant properties.
The N,N'-diacetylated derivative of chitobiose, but with no stereodesignation for the anomeric carbon atom.
A ketone that is alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 2-aminobenzoyl group.
An acyl-CoA resulting from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 4-acetamidobutanoic acid.
A phytoecdysteroid that consists of 5beta-cholesta-8,14-dien-6-one bearing five hydroxy substituents at positions 2, 3, 20, 22 and 25.
An androstanoid that is androst-5-ene substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3 and an oxo group at position 17. It is a naturally occurring steroid hormone produced by the adrenal glands.
A glycopentaosylceramide having alpha-L-Fuc-(1->2)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc as the glycopentaosyl component.

A deoxycortisol that is 17xi-pregn-4-ene-3,20-dione substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 11 and an alpha-hydroxy group at position 17. It is a marker of virilizing adrenal hyperplasia caused by 21-hydroxylase deficiency.
A choloyl-CoA formed by thioester linkage between chenodeoxycholic acid and coenzyme A.
A L-leucine derivative obtained by the substitution of a t-butoxycarbonyl group on the nitrogen atom.
A disaccharide derivative that is (S)-naringenin substituted by a 6-O-(6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of trans-hex-2-enoic acid.
A member of the class of catechols that is catechol in which one of the hydrogens that is ortho to a hydroxy group has been replaced by an isopropyl group.
A disaccharide derivative that consists of eriodictyol substituted by a 6-O-(alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A member of the class of  dihydrochalcones that is the 4'-methyl ether derivative of phloretin.
A 3-hydroxylated derivative of 3-methyl-2-oxovaleric acid.
A sulfoximide that is the sulfoximine derivative of an analogue of DL-methionine in which the S-methyl group is replaced by S-butyl.
A hydroxykynurenamine where the hydroxy group is located at the 5-position.
A hexadec-9-enoic acid in which the double bond at position C-9 has cis configuration.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine that is L-carnitine having decanoyl as the acyl substituent.
The L-enantiomer of allothreonine.
A secondary alpha-hydroxy ketone that is adenosine 5'-monophosphate in which the hydroxy group at position 3' is replaced by an oxo group.
D-glycero-D-manno-heptose in which the hydrogen of the primary hydroxy group is substituted by a dihydrogen phosphate group.
A hydroxy-fatty acid formally derived from octacecanoic (stearic) acid by hydroxy substitution at positions 9 and 10.
